<article class="blog-post">
    <section class="post-header">
        <time datetime="2025-10-24">October 24, 2025</time>
        <h1>ADA Website Lawsuits Surge 37% in 2025: Legal Risks, Trends, and Business Impact</h1>
    </section>
    
    <section id="intro">
        <p>The litigation landscape for web accessibility has fundamentally shifted. What began as a niche legal concern is now a mainstream business risk that crosses industries, company sizes, and geographies. In the first half of 2025 alone, 2,014 ADA website accessibility lawsuits were filed—a 37% increase from the same period in 2024. By the end of 2024, the cumulative total exceeded 4,000 lawsuits filed that year alone. Since 2021, more than 25,000 lawsuits with digital accessibility complaints have been filed across U.S. courts.</p>
        
        <p>For business leaders, this is not a theoretical risk. This is a concrete legal exposure that's accelerating, spreading geographically, and hitting businesses of all sizes. Understanding the current litigation landscape is essential for protecting your organization.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="scale">
        <h2>The Scale of the Problem: 2024-2025 Lawsuit Data</h2>
        
        <p>In 2024, over 4,000 ADA lawsuits related to digital properties were filed across state and federal courts. This represents continued growth in a decade-long trend of increasing digital accessibility litigation. The data breaks down as follows: approximately 2,400 lawsuits were filed in federal courts and 1,600 in state courts. However, a critical shift occurred—state court filings are growing in prominence, particularly in New York and California, which collectively account for 40% of all digital accessibility lawsuits.</p>
        
        <p>But 2024 was just the beginning. In the first six months of 2025, litigation accelerated dramatically. EcomBack's 2025 Mid-Year Report documented 2,014 lawsuits filed between January and June 2025—meaning that 2025 is on track to exceed 4,000 lawsuits for a full year. This 37% year-over-year increase suggests that digital accessibility litigation is not slowing down—it's accelerating.</p>
        
        <p>Notably, this growth is concentrated. Just 31 plaintiffs and 16 law firms were responsible for half of all lawsuits filed in the first half of 2025. This concentration means that certain plaintiffs and firms have developed sophisticated litigation strategies and infrastructure. They're actively hunting for inaccessible websites, filing suits systematically, and pursuing aggressive settlement strategies.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="geographic">
        <h2>Geographic Concentration and State-Level Trends</h2>
        
        <p>ADA website accessibility litigation is not evenly distributed across the country. Certain states have become hotspots for litigation—and the landscape is shifting.</p>
        
        <p><strong>New York Dominance:</strong> New York remains ground zero for ADA digital accessibility lawsuits. In 2024, New York accounted for more lawsuits than California and Florida combined. The state's courts accept cases against any website visited by a New York resident, regardless of where the company is headquartered. This jurisdictional reach, combined with a concentration of plaintiff law firms with offices in New York (six of the ten firms handling most plaintiff suits are New York-based), makes the state uniquely litigious. By the first half of 2025, New York had filed 637 lawsuits, accounting for 31.63% of all filings.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Florida's Surge:</strong> Florida has experienced a dramatic rise in lawsuits. The state climbed from 265 cases in 2024 to 487 in the first half of 2025—nearly doubling its volume and surpassing California to become the second most litigious state for digital accessibility. This surge suggests either an increase in plaintiff activity targeting Florida or improved tracking of cases. Either way, Florida is now a significant legal risk for businesses.</p>
        
        <p><strong>California's Persistent Activity:</strong> California remains highly active but with an important legal caveat. California courts have ruled that online-only businesses without physical locations are not covered by the ADA, making it difficult to pursue cases against pure e-commerce players. However, California still saw increases in filings (rising from 255 to 380 in the first half of 2025), suggesting litigation against companies with physical nexus or operations in the state.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Illinois's Explosive Growth:</strong> Illinois experienced a shocking 745% increase in ADA website accessibility lawsuits in the first half of 2025 compared to the same period in 2024—climbing from 28 to 237 cases. This dramatic spike suggests coordinated litigation activity by specific law firms targeting Illinois businesses, signaling a significant shift in enforcement trends. Illinois is now firmly positioned as a top-four state for digital accessibility lawsuits.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Expanding Beyond Traditional Hotspots:</strong> Minnesota, Missouri, and Pennsylvania have seen increases. Missouri recorded zero lawsuits in the first half of 2024 but experienced 48 cases in the first half of 2025. This expansion suggests that litigation is no longer confined to a few states—it's spreading geographically as more plaintiffs and law firms identify opportunities in underexplored markets.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="industry">
        <h2>Who Gets Sued: Industry and Company Size Targets</h2>
        
        <p><strong>E-Commerce Dominance:</strong> E-commerce websites remain the primary target of ADA lawsuits, representing 77% of all 2024 litigation. Why? Because accessibility barriers are easy to identify and demonstrate during shopping transactions. Poor color contrast on product pages, missing alt text on product images, inaccessible checkout processes, and keyboard navigation barriers directly impact whether customers can complete purchases. Demonstrating damages is straightforward for plaintiffs—they simply show that they couldn't use the website to shop.</p>
        
        <p>E-commerce businesses face particular risk because:</p>
        
        <p>They frequently update features and content, constantly introducing new accessibility barriers. Physical retail locations connected to e-commerce sites increase legal exposure. Their business model relies on digital transactions, making accessibility failures immediately apparent to users and plaintiffs.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Company Size Distribution Shifting:</strong> Historically, small businesses represented the majority of defendants. In 2023, 77% of ADA lawsuits targeted companies with under $25 million in revenue. However, this is changing. In the first half of 2025, 36% of sued companies had annual revenue exceeding $25 million, up from 33% in 2024. This shift suggests that plaintiffs are increasingly targeting larger companies with more resources and deeper pockets to settle lawsuits. Larger companies are becoming attractive defendants, while smaller businesses, though still targeted, now represent a smaller share of litigation.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Industries Beyond E-Commerce:</strong> While e-commerce dominates, lawsuits are spreading across industries. Healthcare providers face significant liability—patient portals, appointment scheduling systems, and medical information websites must be accessible. Financial services companies face lawsuits over inaccessible banking portals and investment platforms. Travel and hospitality sites are targeted. Media companies dealing with video content and accessibility requirements face lawsuits over caption quality and accuracy. Educational institutions face suits over learning management systems and course materials. No industry is exempt.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="accessibility-overlays">
        <h2>The Accessibility Widget Trap: Why Overlays Increase Legal Risk</h2>
        
        <p>One of the most striking trends in 2024-2025 litigation is the explosion of lawsuits targeting companies using accessibility overlays or widgets. In 2024, 1,023 companies using accessibility widgets or overlays were sued—representing more than 25% of all website ADA lawsuits. That proportion continued climbing in 2025, with lawsuits targeting overlay users increasing consistently month-over-month compared to 2024.</p>
        
        <p>This trend matters because many businesses installed these tools specifically to reduce legal risk. They believed that adding an overlay widget would shield them from lawsuits. The opposite has occurred—being identified as an overlay user appears to increase the likelihood of being sued.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Why Overlays Increase Legal Exposure:</strong></p>
        
        <p><strong>Plaintiffs use overlays as evidence of knowledge.</strong> When a company has installed an accessibility widget, it suggests the company was aware that accessibility is important and attempted to address it. Yet if underlying accessibility issues remain (which they typically do, since overlays don't fix structural accessibility problems), plaintiffs can argue the company knew about accessibility requirements but chose an ineffective "quick fix" rather than actually addressing barriers. This suggests bad faith.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Overlays often create new barriers.</strong> As mentioned in overlay discussions, these tools frequently introduce new accessibility problems through their own user interfaces, confusing accessibility settings, and modifications to the DOM that break assistive technology compatibility. Plaintiffs can sue not just for the original barriers but also for barriers introduced by the overlay tool itself.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Overlays don't provide legal protection.</strong> Courts increasingly recognize that overlays don't achieve WCAG compliance. Lawsuits against overlay-using companies often cite the overlay as ineffective and as evidence that the company failed to take accessibility seriously. The Federal Trade Commission even fined a leading overlay provider $1 million in January 2025 for making misleading claims about compliance.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Plaintiffs specifically target overlay users.</strong> Plaintiff law firms have identified that overlay-using companies represent attractive targets because the companies have demonstrated concern about accessibility but failed to fix it properly. It's a signal that sends a clear message: this company is vulnerable to litigation.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="repeat-litigation">
        <h2>The Repeat Litigation Trap: Being Sued Multiple Times</h2>
        
        <p>One of the most devastating trends for businesses is repeat litigation. In 2024, 41% of federal court cases filed were against companies that had been sued for accessibility violations before. Companies received 961 repeat lawsuits, representing over 40% of all cases.</p>
        
        <p>This creates a vicious cycle: A company is sued for accessibility violations. They settle. Yet they don't comprehensively fix the underlying accessibility issues. Months or years later, new plaintiffs discover the same (or different) accessibility barriers. The company is sued again.</p>
        
        <p>Why does this happen? Several reasons:</p>
        
        <p>Companies may make targeted fixes to the specific barriers cited in the original lawsuit but fail to address broader accessibility issues. They may implement an accessibility overlay as a "band-aid" rather than a real fix. They may fail to establish systematic accessibility processes to prevent new barriers from being introduced as the site is updated. A first lawsuit doesn't shield a company from subsequent litigation—it simply signals to other plaintiffs that the company is vulnerable.</p>
        
        <p>The repeat litigation problem is so pervasive that it's become a predictable cost of doing business for some companies. Rather than fixing accessibility properly, some companies budget for ongoing settlements with new plaintiffs. This is not a sustainable strategy—and it destroys the company's reputation and customer relationships in the process.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="damages">
        <h2>The Financial Reality: Settlement Amounts and Costs</h2>
        
        <p>What do accessibility lawsuits cost? Settlement amounts vary widely depending on the company size, scope of violations, and negotiating dynamics, but the data paints a picture of substantial financial exposure.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Individual Settlements:</strong> Publicly disclosed settlements have ranged from tens of thousands to millions of dollars. A 2024 class action settlement involving self-service kiosks resulted in a plaintiff fee petition exceeding $10 million. Major retailers have settled for seven figures. Financial services companies have paid significant sums. Even smaller companies typically settle for amounts that exceed their accessibility remediation costs—meaning the lawsuit cost more than it would have cost to fix the problem.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Hidden Costs Beyond Settlement:</strong> The direct settlement is only part of the cost. Companies must also pay: attorney's fees (often substantial for plaintiff's firms who file 50+ cases per year), expert witnesses, document discovery and litigation costs, management time devoted to the lawsuit, and reputational damage. Many companies report that the total cost of handling an accessibility lawsuit—including legal fees, settlement, and internal costs—exceeds the settlement amount itself.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Serial Litigation Cost:</strong> For companies hit with multiple lawsuits, cumulative costs become staggering. A company sued four or five times for the same underlying issues can face settlement costs in the millions, plus the legal fees and management time.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="compliance-standards">
        <h2>The Compliance Standard: WCAG 2.1 AA (With Title II Deadline Looming)</h2>
        
        <p>Lawsuits are typically filed citing failure to meet Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.1. Most federal cases reference WCAG 2.1 AA compliance as the standard, though some plaintiffs pursue claims based on AAA (higher) standards. Several state courts are also recognizing state-specific accessibility laws that add additional compliance obligations.</p>
        
        <p>A critical date is April 2026, when the Department of Justice's ADA Title II final rule requires state and local governments to conform to WCAG 2.1 AA. This deadline will likely expand litigation as agencies struggle to meet the requirement. However, there's already debate about whether WCAG 2.1 AA is sufficiently forward-looking or whether it's become outdated relative to modern web technologies, AI systems, and emerging accessibility needs.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="defense-challenges">
        <h2>Legal Defense Challenges and Jurisdictional Issues</h2>
        
        <p><strong>Physical Nexus Questions:</strong> For years, there was ambiguity about whether the ADA applied to websites at all. Recent court decisions have clarified this somewhat, but significant uncertainty remains. A 2024 New York federal court decision (Mejia v. High Brew Coffee) ruled that web-only businesses without physical locations are not covered under ADA Title III, creating a carve-out for pure e-commerce players. However, this decision conflicts with earlier rulings and may not hold up on appeal. Businesses remain unsure about their legal exposure depending on jurisdiction and business model.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Forum Shopping.</strong> Plaintiff law firms strategically choose venues. New York courts have historically been plaintiff-friendly. California courts have developed case law creating carve-outs for web-only businesses. Different federal circuits have different approaches. Plaintiffs understand these nuances and file in jurisdictions most favorable to their claims.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Serial Plaintiff Litigation.</strong> Certain plaintiffs have become extremely prolific. One law firm (So Cal Equal Access Group) filed 2,598 federal ADA Title III lawsuits in 2024—accounting for more than half of all federal digital accessibility lawsuits. This concentration suggests the litigation is driven more by law firm strategy and business model than by comprehensive enforcement of accessibility standards. Defendants argue this represents an abuse of the legal system designed to coerce quick settlements. However, courts have generally been reluctant to dismiss these cases on grounds of abuse of process.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="avoiding-risk">
        <h2>Reducing Legal Exposure: What Businesses Should Do Now</h2>
        
        <p><strong>1. Conduct a Comprehensive Manual WCAG Audit</strong></p>
        
        <p>Don't rely on automated scanning tools. While automated tools can detect roughly 30% of WCAG violations, they miss 70% of issues. A comprehensive manual audit by accessibility experts who understand both code and user impact is essential. This audit should identify all WCAG 2.1 AA violations—not just a sample of issues.</p>
        
        <p><strong>2. Avoid Accessibility Overlays and Widgets</strong></p>
        
        <p>If your website currently uses an accessibility overlay or widget, seriously consider removing it. As discussed, these tools increase rather than decrease litigation risk. Replace the overlay with actual remediation of accessibility issues.</p>
        
        <p><strong>3. Prioritize Remediation Based on Impact</strong></p>
        
        <p>Once you know what needs fixing, prioritize based on impact—not just severity. Color contrast failures affect many users with vision impairment. Missing alt text on critical product images affects blind users' ability to shop. Keyboard navigation failures affect multiple disability types. Focus first on the barriers that have the greatest impact on real user experience.</p>
        
        <p><strong>4. Act Quickly After Receiving a Demand Letter or Lawsuit</strong></p>
        
        <p>If you receive a demand letter or are sued, take it seriously and respond promptly. Companies that address accessibility issues quickly after a first lawsuit are significantly less likely to face repeat litigation. Ignoring the issue or making only cosmetic fixes guarantees you'll be sued again.</p>
        
        <p><strong>5. Establish Ongoing Accessibility Processes</strong></p>
        
        <p>Accessibility isn't a one-time fix. It requires ongoing processes: training for developers and content creators, accessibility review of new features before launch, regular audits to catch new issues, and a culture that prioritizes inclusion. Companies that build accessibility into their development process don't need to worry as much about litigation—they simply don't have significant accessibility barriers.</p>
        
        <p><strong>6. Document Your Good Faith Efforts</strong></p>
        
        <p>While documentation doesn't prevent lawsuits, it can help in defense. Document your accessibility audit, your remediation efforts, your training, your governance processes, and your commitment to ongoing improvement. Courts recognize good faith efforts even if perfect compliance hasn't been achieved.</p>
    </section>
    
    <section id="forward">
        <h2>2025 and Beyond: The Litigation Trajectory</h2>
        
        <p>Several factors suggest that accessibility litigation will continue to escalate:</p>
        
        <p>The April 2026 Title II deadline will force government agencies to undertake major compliance efforts, which will likely expose widespread non-compliance and spark additional litigation. Plaintiff law firms have perfected their litigation infrastructure and continue to expand geographically. Courts have become increasingly receptive to these cases, establishing clearer precedent. More businesses are adopting digital engagement (post-pandemic shift to e-commerce and digital services), creating larger attack surfaces for plaintiffs. The growth of AI and new web technologies creates new accessibility challenges that websites haven't yet adapted to.</p>
        
        <p>For business leaders, the message is clear: the days of ignoring web accessibility are over. The financial, legal, and reputational costs of non-compliance are real and measurable. Organizations that prioritize genuine accessibility today will avoid the substantially higher costs of litigation tomorrow.</p>
    </section>
    
